{"analytics_identifier":null,"base_path":"/government/history/past-prime-ministers/william-wyndham-grenville-1st-baron-grenville","content_id":"d4b44e15-3c7c-41b1-969a-aad0521277c1","description":"On his resignation: “The deed is done and I am again a free man, and to you I may express what it would seem like affection to say to others, the infinite pleasure I derive from emancipation.”","details":{"body":"<div class=\"govspeak\"><p>William Wyndham Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville was the son of <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/history/past-prime-ministers/george-grenville\" class=\"govuk-link\">George Grenville</a>, an earlier Prime Minister.</p>\n\n<p>Despite the brevity of his time as Prime Minister, William Grenville’s extended political career highlights the shifting patterns of British political alignments in the later Hanoverian period. As premier, he was responsible for one of the most important legislative measures of the early nineteenth century, the abolition of the slave trade in 1807.</p>\n\n<p>Read more about William Grenville on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://history.blog.gov.uk/2015/10/14/william-wyndham-grenville-whig-1806-1807/\" class=\"govuk-link\">History of government blog</a>.</p>\n</div>","born":"25 October 1759 , Buckinghamshire","dates_in_office":[{"end_year":1807,"start_year":1806}],"died":"12 January 1834, Buckinghamshire","interesting_facts":"","major_acts":"Slave Trade Act 1807: abolished the slave trade in the British Empire. ","political_party":"Whig"},"document_type":"historic_appointment","first_published_at":"2023-01-19T17:38:34+00:00","links":{"available_translations":[{"api_path":"/api/content/government/history/past-prime-ministers/william-wyndham-grenville-1st-baron-grenville","api_url":"https://www.gov.uk/api/content/government/history/past-prime-ministers/william-wyndham-grenville-1st-baron-grenville","base_path":"/government/history/past-prime-ministers/william-wyndham-grenville-1st-baron-grenville","content_id"